title: For Sale:  1000 pieces of 300 Blackout Brass
postcontent: This, in my honest opinion, is the one of the best options of brass for blackout. This brass is 100% WCC made from once fired 5.56. It has a stronger primer pocket compared to the other brass I run and I seem to get more reloadings from it comparatively. Primer pockets are swagged, not reemed, just enough that the primers go in while still giving it a snug fit for long life. I trim the brass to 1.355 which is closer to the lower tolerance so your brass should last longer between trimmings. The way these are trimmed some might have a slight burr on the inside of the case. These can be removed with a deburring chamfer or running them through a resizing die. I dont think it necessarily needs removed and I dont when I reload them. Shipping is not included but flat rate is pretty reasonable. I take PayPal (gift or +3.5%) or postal mo. PayPal however will get you the fastest shipping. This is made to order so shipping will not be immediate. I might have more at a later date. No trades at this time, email me if you want a smaller lot but that rates are higher

This upper receiver traces its origins back some six years to guns Colt produced for the SCAR (Special Operations Forces Combat Assault Rifle) program of the U.S. Special Operations Command (SOCOM). And the monolithic upper weighs less than a standard upper receiver with separate quad-rail handguard attached. The upper, made from a CNC-machined 7075-T6 aluminum forging, features integral top and side Picatinny rails extending forward just to the rear of the gas block. Recesses for quick-detachable sling swivels are located on both side rails. The bottom rail is a separate piece that can be detached for cleaning or installation of under-barrel accessories. All rail sections have numbered slots for repeatable installation of devices. The LE6940 has extensive parts commonality with the M4, sharing the barrel’s chrome-lining, four-position collapsible stock, and birdcage-style flash hider. Also present are the familiar shell deflector, ejection port cover and forward assist. The LE6940’s bolt, carrier and trigger mechanism also follow the proven AR-15 pattern, as do the controls on the lower receiver: magazine release, reversible safety and bolt release. Like all current Colt-produced rifles, the LE6940 uses 0.154-inch-diameter hammer and trigger pins. The 1:7-inch twist of the barrel and 5.56x45 mm NATO chamber allow the use of 55-grain, 62-grain and 77-grain ammunition. postcontent:
OFFERED FOR SALE FROM NC23GUNS!

Type Double Action semiautomatic 
Caliber(s) 7.65x17mmSR (.32ACP) 
Weight unloaded 710 g 
Length 167 mm 
Barrel length 96 mm 
Magazine capacity 8 rounds 



The small, pocket-sized Vz.50 was developed during late 1940s for police use and it was chambered for the marginally powerful 7.65x17 Browning ammunition. Apparently influenced by the Walther PP in design, the Vz.50 had several differences in safety and disassembly. In the early 1970s the basic design went through minor face-lift, and the “new” design received the designation of Vz.70. Many Vz.50 pistols were refurbished to Vz.70 standard, with different finish, grip panels and a slightly different safety lever. New Vz.70 pistols were also manufactured between 1970 and 1983. After the replacement in service of the older Vz.50 and Vz.70 by more modern 9mm Vz.82 pistol, most were sold as surplus, as Cz-50 and Cz-70, respectively.

The Vz.50 (commercially sold as Cz-50) is a compact pistol of all-steel construction, firing the relatively weak 7.65mm ammunition. It has a simple blowback action with a fixed barrel. The trigger is double-action, with an exposed hammer and a frame-mounted decocking safety lever. The sights are fixed. Magazines are single stack. The magazine release button is located relatively high on the left side of the frame, behind the trigger. Vz.70 (Cz-70) pistols are similar, with minor differences in the finish, shape of the safety lever and grips. Manual safety is a lever at left side of the frame, behind the trigger guard. To set on safe: pull the lever down; if the hammer was cocked, it will be automatically brought down to rest. To disengage safety: push the lever up; a red dot will appear on the frame.

How to field-strip (disassemble) Cz-50 and Cz-70 pistol: 1) remove the magazine by pressing the magazine release button; 2) check that the chamber is empty; 3) push the disassembly button, located at the right side of the frame, above the front of the trigger-guard; 4) while holding the disassembly button, retract the slide all the way back, raise the rear part of the slide off the rails, then slowly release it forward and off the barrel; 5) remove the return spring from the barrel
 Reassemble in reverse order

title: For Sale:  VERY NICE 1966 Ruger .44 Magnum Carbine 44 mag with box of ammo
postcontent:
* IF YOU ARE INTERESTED IN THIS GUN MAKE AN OFFER SOON. I HAVE IT SOLD ALREADY AT $650 SO YOU'VE GOT TO OFFER MORE THAN THAT. If you want this gun buy it soon as one way or the other it'll be gone in 5 days. 

Awesome condition 1966 Ruger .44 Magnum carbine. Comes with a full box of hollow point ammo. 

Check out the pictures to see what amazing condition this is in. Serial number starts with 110,xxx so according to Ruger records, it was made in 1966. There is no warning label on this gun. It is a metal and wood gun - no plastic parts, a truly awesome example of American gun manufacturing. Stock is a very nice dark walnut. This is one of the rarer monte carlo or "finger grove" stocks. It has the Ruger logo on the bottom of the knob and sling attachments. Already has weaver rail scope mounts on it so a scope can be attached and the original sights can also be used. Made from 1961-1985 there were two runs of these rifles the first from 1961-1974 and the second from 75-85. This is a fine example of the first run where a tube magazine was used rather than a detachable mag. 

I'm going to try to give a better description as I can only load three pictures. If I had to guess I would say that this rifle was never used to hunt. The sort of wear it has is consistent with someone taking it out to the range once or twice a year for 47 years. It has the sorts of marks that are almost impossible to avoid as you put a gun into and take a gun out of a safe, case, rack, etc. The sort of nicks that happen when you lay it down on a wooden shooting bench, etc. The rifling is awesome and the metal parts all show almost no use. 

Overall I'd put this gun at 90%+. I'd say its between "VERY GOOD" and "Excellent" on the NRA grading scale. This rifle has a few nicks and light scratches that you'd expect from a gun that is 47 years old. The finish is very good, if it looks like there is veneer missing its just the picture. There is about a 1/4 inch chip in the very bottom of the butt stock where the gun meets the butt plate. It is so insignificant that I didn't even notice it until I was inspecting it closer for an interested party. It will only be seen if the gun is literally laying on its top (bottom exposed up). Otherwise just extremely minor surface scratches and nicks. The bluing is excellent everywhere with no noticeable scratches or dings.  

If you have any questions please ask. I will answer as quick as possible.
